<HEAD><title>What Works -- Welfare Reform -- ATR</title></HEAD>
<BODY Bgcolor=#FFFFFF><CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  <BR><FONT SIZE=+3><BOLD>What Works -- Welfare Reform</BOLD></FONT><P></CENTER>
 <IMG ALIGN=TOPRIGHT SRC="wwwelf.gif">Father Robert Sirico<P>

	In Grand Rapids, Mich., the Acton Institute for the Study of Religion and Liberty recently launched a one-year welfare reform program which includes four separate projects.  The first project was a highly successful conference held March 29 in Washington, D.C., attended by 200 welfare policy researchers and administrators.  Key speakers included House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.), Michigan Gov. John Engler (R), and Mayor Stephen Goldsmith (R) of Indianapolis, Ind.  Two other special Acton projects include welfare reform publications and a speaker's tour.<P>
	The fourth project is a national "better charity" competition to recognize "compassionate, effective, and innovative charitable programs."  Father Robert A. Sirico, president of the Acton Institute, announced in May the institute will award $40,000 in grants to individuals and organizations working to solve social and economic problems.<P>
	"Our Samaritan Awards are a way to honor the accomplishments of creative charities and share their techniques and know-how with others seeking to help the needy," said Fr. Sirico.  He noted that the ideal award-winning programs would be those that help individuals strengthen ties with their family, friends, and community and foster self-reliance and self-esteem by addressing both spiritual and material needs.<P>
	Americans for Tax Reform Foundation (ATRF) President Grover Norquist says he welcomes projects like the Acton Institute idea which look for practical solutions to the costly welfare state.  "It's not enough to oppose government-provided welfare systems, we need to find superior alternatives," said Norquist.<P>
	Three winning model programs will each be awarded $10,000 and there will be $1,000 awards for each of ten finalists.  The entry deadline for Samaritan Awards is July 15, 1995.  Applications and more information may be obtained by writing to The Acton Institute, 161 Ottawa Ave., N.W., Suite 301, Grand Rapids, Michigan 49503 or by calling the Institute at 616-454-3080.<P>  

Rabbi Daniel Lapin<p>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="ww1.gif">
<p><p>Mazel Tov, Mr. Speaker 
	In January, Rabbi Daniel Lapin, president of Toward Tradition, met with House Speaker Newt Gingrich and came away heartened by the speaker's receptiveness to this fairly new organization's message: that new public policy initiatives need a moral grounding, which can be found in Scripture and in Jewish religious traditions.  Speaker Gingrich expressed the hope that more Jewish conservatives will take part in the political process.<P>
	Toward Tradition was founded in 1991.  Its membership includes both Jews and Christians who believe that the success of America's experiment in free government, in the service of a just and good society, depends on maintaining the strong foundation of values that are emphasized in the Judeo-Christian heritage.<P>
  	Rabbi Lapin says neither the Jewish community's spiritual heritage nor its practical interests are best served when the community is chiefly aligned with policies that push the excessive growth and power of government at the potential expense of personal freedom.  To emphasize this point, Toward Tradition took out an advertisement in The New York Times on December 16, 1994, which supported the Contract with America.<P>
	The ad was entitled,  "Mazel Tov, Speaker Gingrich -- We Know All About 10 Point Contracts."  <Address>Mazel tov </Address> is Hebrew for congratulations.  While the ad caused controversy in New York and even provoked responding counter advertisements from more liberal Jewish organizations, it nevertheless generated positive responses as well and focused attention on the Contract debate.  A framed copy of the advertisement now hangs in the speaker's office.<P>
	Since January, Rabbi Lapin has been busy on the lecture circuit talking about how spiritual heritage influences policy questions and is writing a new book.  In addition, he has become the regular host of the Monday night (9:00-11:00) talk show slot on radio station KVI in Seattle, Wash.<P>
  	Toward Tradition is planning a major poll of the American Jewish community to survey current attitudes on policy questions since the majorities in Congress changed in January.  It is also planning a second national conference.  Toward Tradition's first conference last October attracted 400 participants.  Organizers are planning for more than double that number this year.<P>
  	For more information, interested readers may write to Rabbi Daniel Lapin, President, Toward Tradition, P.O. Box 58, Mercer Island, Washington 98040. The telephone number is 206-236-3046 and the fax number is 206-236-3288.<P>
	Information may also be obtained from the California office at 110 Newport Center Drive, Suite 200, Newport Beach, California 92660.  Toward Tradition Vice President Michael Lapin's California telephone number is 714-644-0300 and his fax number is 714-644-2224.   Toward Tradition's Washington, D.C. office may be reached by calling Director of Development Yarden Weidenfeld at 202-872-8723. <P>
<P>
<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar.map"><img src="/atr/bar.gif" ismap border="0"></a> </CENTER>
 <P> 
</FONT><ADDRESS><A HREF="MAILTO:atr@townhall.com">Americans for Tax Reform</A><FONT SIZE=3><BOLD> 
<BR>
1320 18th Street NW Suite 200<BR>
Washington, DC 20036<BR></ADDRESS>
