<html>
<head>
<title>PFF Discusses:  Is the Internet Good for You? No. 1.3  September 1996</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<h3>PFF Discusses:  Is the Internet Good for You?</h3>
<b>THE PROGRESS REPORT<BR>
No. 1.3  September 1996	</b>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><a href="#intro">Introduction</a>
<LI><a href="#first">First Panel</a>
<LI><a href="#second">Second Panel</a>
<LI><a href="#toffler">Toffler Explores Political Flexibility</a> 
<LI><a href="#public">Making Public Policy for Cyberspace</a>
<LI><a href="#pull">It's Time to Pull the Plug on Federal Power</a>
<LI><a href="#telecom">PFF Releases Telecom Book, The Innovation Age</a>
<LI><a href="#clean">For Cleaner Air,  PFF Says Think Globally, Act Locally</a>
<LI><a href="#forston">Fortson Joins District Council</a>
<LI><a href="#forbes">Eisenach in Forbes ASAP</a> 
</UL>
<P>
<a name="intro">
<H4>Introduction</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<DD>In an attempt to keep Java, Netscape, Windows 95, the Communications Decency Act, the debate over encryption, Pat Buchanan and the rise of the "New Luddites" in perspective, The Progress & Freedom Foundation convened its Aspen Summit '96:  Cyberspace and the American Dream Conference August 4-6.
More than 150 people gathered in Aspen, Colorado, to explore the promise and peril of the Digital Revolution.  "We want to remind ourselves that America's continued progress in the Digital Revolution is not something to take for granted.  Great civilizations sometimes choose paths leading to decay – even, or perhaps especially, in a digital world," said Foundation President Jeffrey A. Eisenach.
<P>
<a name="first">
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<H4>First Panel</H4>
<P><IMG SRC="/pff/asp-pics/society.gif" ALIGN="left">
<DD>David Gergen of U.S. News & World Report moderated a panel discussion on "Shaping American Society for the Digital Age" that featured Philip Burgess of the Center for the New West, Esther Dyson of EDventure Holdings, David Gelernter of Yale University and Heather Higgins of PFF.
<DD>Dyson described how in the digital world people may need to distinguish between public and private persons.  A private person, using encryption technology as a defense mechanism to protect themselves, is ensured of confidentiality in one-to-one communications like e-mail.  However, when one posts information on the Internet for all to see, offers something to sell, or asks for credit to pay bills, that part of their activity becomes public and will require more disclosure and verification.
Gelernter, a Yale University computer scientist and author of 1939:  The Lost World of the Fair, said that America's biggest problems, our failing education system and struggling families, are things computers cannot deal with.  Basically, Gelernter said, we use computers for word processing, data manipulation, information storage and communication.  However, he asked, "compared to Americans in 1939, are we better writers?  More informed?  Better educated?  Richer communicators?"
After the discussion, Senator Bill Bradley (D-NJ) offered "a practical view" on the how the digital revolution is affecting American society.  "When I walk into a labor hall and a union member tells me that he just lost his manufacturing job, what am I supposed to say? 'Great, now you can go get a knowledge job.'"
<P>
<a name="second">
<BR>
<H4>Second Panel</H4>
<P>
<DD>A second panel discussion at the Summit, moderated by Peter Huber of the Manhattan Institute, featured author George Gilder, Jerry Jasinowski of the National Association of Manufacturers, Rich Karlgaard of Forbes ASAP and Jay Keyworth of PFF.  Les Vadasz of Intel offered the "practical view" of the technologies creating the new economy.
<DD>After a series of working group sessions on Education, Regulatory Convergence, Intellectual Property, and Privacy and Censorship, the Summit concluded with a debate on if the "Growth of the Internet is a 'Leading Cultural Indicator' of Progress."
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<a name="toffler">
<BR>
<H4>Toffler Explores Political Flexibility</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>"What do Hillary Clinton and Newt Gingrich have in common?" asked author Alvin Toffler as he opened PFF's Aspen Summit '96.  "They both promised revolutionary change – Hillary in health care and Newt more broadly – and both were slapped down," he concluded.
<DD>Toffler's speech, titled "Future Shock in the Present Tense," described how Americans feel battered by the very acceleration of the Information Revolution.  "They want a chance to slow down and <IMG SRC="/pff/asp-pics/toffle.gif" ALIGN="left">catch their breath.  People, including companies, are disoriented and grasp after anything" that seems to offer reassurance.
<DD>The American political system, its very structure, Toffler said, is ultra stable and resists change.  "It punishes change makers like Hillary Clinton and Newt Gingrich."  Toffler explored whether Americans want a political system that is more flexible and thus might better adjust to the changes in society being engendered by the Information Revolution.  With too many alienated people, Toffler wondered if more flexibility in America's political structure might be needed to avoid violence.
<DD>Toffler also spoke about the importance of no longer discussing "the future of the economy" because it implies a continuation of the industrial age, but instead to focus on "the economy of the future," which will compel a redefinition of basic economic fundamentals.
<DD>In conclusion, Toffler said that the Information Age is shattering existing cultures around the world, and while we can "remain American, we cannot remain Americans of the past but will be Americans of the future."
<P>
<a name="public">
<P>
<H4>Making Public Policy for Cyberspace</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<DD>Representative Rick White (R-WA), co-chair of the bi-cameral and bi-partisan <IMG SRC="/pff/asp-pics/bradley.gif" ALT="Rep. Rick White and Sen. Bill Bradley at Aspen Summit '96"  ALIGN="right">Congressional Internet Caucus, addressed the Chairman's Dinner at PFF's Aspen Summit '96.  White urged the high-tech audience to learn how to effectively deal with Congress.  Until recently, the computer industry did not need to interact much with Washington, White said, but with their success has come increased government involvement in the industry.
<P>
<BR>
<a name="pull">
<P>
<BR>
<H4>It's Time to Pull the Plug on Federal Power</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>Declaring that federally owned power facilities created during the New Deal have accomplished their mission, PFF released a white paper urging their privatization.  The <IMG SRC="/pff/asp-pics/1.gif" ALT="Rep. John Shadegg"  ALIGN=right>paper, co-authored by Representative John Shadegg (R-AZ) and Foundation Senior Fellow Michael Block, proposes a privatization method modeled on Czech experience, where consumers receive a portion of the money from privatization.
<DD>Power Marketing Administrations (PMA's) were designed to provide a supply of inexpensive power to impoverished rural areas; today, many of the once underdeveloped areas are affluent.   "PMAs' assets are of significant value to the private electric energy industry and, if sold by the government, would increase operating efficiency, eliminate market distortions, advance competition in electricity markets, and generate significant revenue for federal deficit reduction," argues the paper.
<DD>The paper – Lights Out on Federal Power:  Privatization for the   21st Century – outlines how the federal government should sell three PMA's, generating nearly $4.5 billion to reduce the budget deficit. 
<P>
<a name="telecom">
<P>
<H4>PFF Releases Telecom Book, The Innovation Age</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>Peter K. Pitsch, PFF Adjunct Fellow and former Chief of Staff and Research Director at the FCC, authored the newly released Innovation Age:  A New Perspective on the Telecom Revolution.
<DD>Advancements in computer and digital information technologies have created an era of rapid economic, technological and social change that Pitsch calls the "Innovation Age."  Economic growth in this realm, argues Pitsch, depends on constant innovation and competition; therefore, government efforts to regulate these new technologies should adapt to reflect this new paradigm.
<DD>"Today's complexity and change make Hayek's 'spontaneous order' and Schumpeter's 'creative destruction' more compelling than ever before.  Peter Pitsch combines these concepts in a new economics of innovation that provides an illuminating view of telecom – both how to understand it and why market forces will regulate it best," says author George Gilder about The Innovation Age.
<P>
<a name="clean">
<P>
<H4>For Cleaner Air,  PFF Says Think Globally, Act Locally</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>A new PFF white paper urges the creation of local Environmental Innovation Areas (EIAs) that recognize the variation in environmental conditions across America and thus will serve to solve regional pollution problems.  The paper calls for using EIAs as a means of promoting alternative fuel vehicles to meet clean air requirements and petroleum import reduction goals.
<DD>"Different regions face different pollution problems, and thus they must be given the flexibility to meet clean air requirements in ways best suited for their region," said Bruce Yandle, a co-author of the white paper, titled Clean Air and Emerging Alternative Fuel Vehicles:  A Time for Environmental Innovation Areas. 
<DD>"Alternative fuel – or non petroleum-based – vehicles pollute less and should serve as an important component of many regions' strategies for meeting clean air goals," says the paper.
<P>
<a name="forston">
<P>
<H4>Fortson Joins District Council</H4>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>Senior Fellow Jane Fortson, director of PFF's Social and Cultural Studies, continues her involvement in urban issues and the District of Columbia.  She recently joined other District leaders as a founding board member of the DC Agenda Support Corporation, an organization modeled after the highly successful Fund for the City of New York.  Additionally, she is participating in an advisory group examining revenue issues for the District, sponsored by the Brookings Institution.
<P>
<a name="forbes">
<P>
<H4>Eisenach in Forbes ASAP </H4>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>"Kakumei:  Renewing rules and order.  It is a more comforting concept, to be sure, than 'revolution,' But it also more accurate.  Kakumei, not 'revolution' is the next challenge of the digital age."
<DD>Excerpted from PFF Jeff Eisenach's article in the December Forbes ASAP — available on-line now at <a href="http://www.forbesasap.com">www.forbesasap.com</a> .
<P>
<BR>
