<HEAD>

<TITLE>Cyberspace and the American Dream -- PFF</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Rick F. O'Donnell">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Michael Sparks">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<map name="cft">
<area shape="rect" coords="0,0,92,20" href="#cyber">
<area shape="rect" coords="93,0,193,20" href="#fcc">
<area shape="rect" coords="194,0,318,20" href="#telco"></map>

<blockquote>

<a href="welcome.html"><img src="bi.gif" align="right" border="0" alt="PFF"></a>
<center>
<a href="wst.map"><img src="cft.gif" border="0" USEMAP="#cft" ISMAP></a>
<img src="cadhead.gif" alt="Cyberspace and the American Dream">
</center>
<br><br><P>
Much of our recent work on telecom has been enhanced by the  
<a href = "http://www.pff.org/pff/workin~1.htm"><big>FCC Working Group.</big></a>

<p>

<table>
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="20%">PFF is working to describe what a Transformation of American Life
driven by the new technologies of the information revolution really
means.  How will it change our fundamental values and beliefs?
 Society's elemental relationships?   The organization and workings
of our economy?  And our political compact with ourselves [or
is it, after all, between us and the state]?
<P>
If we can describe what is to come, we can show what is to be
done.  In addition, policy change is taking place in Washington,
in state legislatures, indeed, in governments around the world,
as policymakers attempt to understand the consequences of the
move from an analog to a digital world and its impact on regulatory
policy.  PFF is actively involved in the telecommunications debate,
focusing on the next generation of deregulation.
<td valign="top">
<a name="cyber"></a>
<img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><big>The Nature of Cyberspace</big>
<UL>



<img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top">
<b><a href="/pff/21fcc1.html">The FCC and the Telecommunications Act of 1996: Putting Competition on Hold?</a></b>
by G.A. Keyworth, II and Jeffrey A. Eisenach<br>
<img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top">
<b><a href="/pff/encry.html">The Computer Revolution, Encryption And
True Threats To National Security</a></b>
by G.A. Keyworth, II and
David E. Colton, Esq.<br>  
<img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vsapce="4" align="top"><b><a href="/pff/cad/pr0620.html">Administration Undermines Information Age National Security</a></b><br>
