<title>PARENTAL RIGHTS: WHO DECIDES HOW CHILDREN ARE RAISED?</title>

<body>

<center>

<img src="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampolbl.gif">

<h1>Parental Rights:</h1>
<h2><i>Who Decides How Children Are Raised?</i></h2>

</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>F</font>rom ancient times to modernity, political philosophy 
has grappled with the sensitive relationship between the child, family, 
and state.  In <I>The Republic</I>, Plato wrote:

<p><blockquote>

<i>&quot;The wives of our guardians are to be common, and their
children are to be common, and no parent is to know his own child,
nor any child his parent. . . .  The proper officers will take
the offspring of the good parents to the pen or fold, and there
they will deposit them with certain nurses who dwell in a separate
quarter.&quot;</i>

</blockquote><p>

In <I>Orthodoxy</I>, G.K. Chesterton observed:

<p><blockquote>

<i>&quot;In short, the democratic faith is this:  that the
most terribly important things must be left to ordinary men themselves
-- the mating of the sexes, the rearing of the young, the laws
of the state.&quot;</i>

</blockquote><p>

Like Plato, modern-day utopian thinkers and totalitarian
states have always looked upon the parent-child relationship with
suspicion at best, and more often as the crucial obstacle to ultimate
state power over the individual.  For even if the state is successful
in dissolving all other institutions which mediate between the
individual and state, such as local government, the church, and
private associations, it must still contend with the family unit
as the last bastion of organic relationships from which spring
an individual's prior loyalties.  Because a totalitarian regime
can admit of no prior loyalties, ultimately the natural bonds
between husband and wife, and parent and child must also be dissolved,
reducing even children to the status of atomized individuals,
helpless before the Leviathan.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Respect for the autonomy<br>
of the family is as<br>
central to the democratic<br>
ideal as popular sovereignty.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Conversely, as Chesterton so eloquently expressed, respect
for the autonomy of the family is as central to the democratic
ideal as popular sovereignty.  The democratic experiment is founded
on an optimism in the ability of the people to manage their own
affairs, in their capacity as citizens with authority over &quot;the
laws of the state,&quot; and in their capacity as parents with
authority over &quot;the rearing of the young.&quot;  Therefore,
restoring parental rights to its original firm foundation in U.S.
constitutional law is crucial to our overall efforts to reinvigorate
the democratic ideal of citizenship.

<p>

<center><h3>The Constitutional Roots of Parental Rights</h3></center>

<p>

Parental liberty as a fundamental right found a secure place
in U.S. constitutional jurisprudence beginning with two Supreme
Court cases from the 1920s.  The 1923 decision in <I>Meyer v.
Nebraska</I>[1] involved a challenge to a Nebraska state law which
prohibited the teaching of foreign languages in any school --
public or private -- prior to the eighth grade.  In determining
whether or not the foreign-language prohibition unreasonably infringed
upon family rights,[2] the Supreme Court declared that the 14th Amendment
liberty interest &quot;[w]ithout doubt, [] denotes not merely
freedom from bodily restraint but also the right of the individual
to contract, to engage in any of the common occupations of life,
to acquire useful knowledge, to marry, establish a home and bring
up children.&quot;[3] The Court held that the Nebraska statute interfered
with the parents' fundamental right to raise their children, including
the right to have their children learn a foreign language.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
With the parental<br>
responsibility to protect<br>
their children from harm<br>
comes the parental right<br>
to direct their children's<br>
upbringing and education.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Two years later, in <I>Pierce v. Society of Sisters,</I>[4] the
Court examined an Oregon state statute compelling parents to send
their children to public schools from ages 8 to 16 -- essentially
banning private education.[5]  While acknowledging that the State
has the authority to enact reasonable regulations to ensure the
basic education of the citizenry,[6] the Court held that in this
instance state authority must yield to the rights of parents.
&quot;Under the doctrine of <I>Meyer v. Nebraska</I>, we think
it entirely plain that the [Oregon state] Act of 1922 unreasonably
interferes with the liberty of parents and guardians to direct
the upbringing and education of children under their control&quot;[7]
(citations omitted). The Court stated:

<p><blockquote>

<i>The fundamental theory of liberty upon which all governments
in this Union repose excludes any general power of the State to
standardize its children by forcing them to accept instruction
from public teachers only.  The child is not the mere creature
of the State; those who nurture him and direct his destiny have
the right, coupled with the high duty, to recognize and prepare
him for additional obligations.</i>[8]

</blockquote><p>

A generation passed before the high court issued another landmark
parental rights decision, <I>Prince v. Massachusetts</I>.[9] The
Court ruled in favor of state authority over the asserted parental
right of Sarah Prince, a Jehovah's Witness.  Prince was the guardian
of a 9-year-old girl whom she took with her to sell religious
pamphlets on the street.  When charged with violating state child
labor laws, Prince claimed that the law violated her religious
freedom and parental rights.  The Court, citing <I>Pierce</I>,
acknowledged parental rights in the strongest terms:

<p><blockquote>

<i>It is cardinal with us that the custody, care and nurture
of the child reside first in the parents, whose primary function
and freedom include preparation for obligations the state can
neither supply nor hinder.  And it is in recognition of this that
these decisions have respected the private realm of family life
which the state cannot enter&quot; (citations omitted).</i>[10]

</blockquote><p>

Despite this reaffirmation, the Court recognized that the state
may act to protect children by &quot;limiting parental freedom
and authority in things affecting the child's welfare&quot;[11] 
including protecting the child from &quot;the crippling effects of 
child employment,&quot; especially in public places.[12]

<p>

In 1972, the Supreme Court again considered a case involving
overlapping issues of parental rights and religious freedom.
In <I>Wisconsin v. Yoder</I>,[13] Amish families desired to remove
their children from school after the eighth grade, violating Wisconsin's
compulsory education law.[14] The Court declared:

<p><blockquote>

<i>Indeed it seems clear that if the State is empowered, as</I> 
parens patriae, <I>to &quot;save&quot; a child from himself
or his Amish parents by requiring an additional two years of compulsory
formal high school education, the State will in large measure
influence, if not determine, the religious future of the child.
Even more markedly than in Prince, therefore, this case involves
the fundamental interest of parents, as contrasted with that of
the State, to guide the religious future and education of their
children.</i>[15]

</blockquote><p>

While recognizing the State's &quot;high responsibility for
education of its citizens,&quot;[16] the Court concluded that this
interest did not outweigh the Amish parents' religious beliefs
and parent liberty interest in directing the education of their
children.[17]

<p>

<center><h3>The Modern Assault on Parental Rights</h3></center>

<p>

The state laws overturned by the high court in <I>Meyer</I>
and <I>Pierce</I> were generated by racial and religious tensions
typical of the 1920s (<I>Meyer</I> dealt with anti-German sentiment
following World War I, and <I>Pierce</I>, the anti-Catholicism
of the age).  Recent conflicts between parents and the state involve
a broad range of matters at the very heart of the parent-child
relationship.  The growing parental backlash against schools and
other government bureaucracies is best understood as part of the
overall struggle parents face as they attempt to transmit their
most cherished beliefs to their children in the midst of an anti-family
culture.

<p>

Many social commentators have focused attention on our degraded
popular culture, and it is widely recognized that parents face
an increasingly difficult task in monitoring their children's
exposure to the barrage of harmful images produced by Hollywood,
pop music, and the Internet.  But while a national debate rages
over the proper response to the polluted commercial marketplace,
relatively little attention has been focused on the fact that
too often parents have discovered that their own <I>government</I>
is part of the problem.  Increasingly, parents are demanding that
government policies support, rather than undermine, their authority.

<p>

The past generation has witnessed the growth of  two overlapping
trends in public policy which have significantly undermined parental
authority and family autonomy.  The first is exemplified by laws
giving minors access to abortion and birth control without parental
approval, and in looming threats like the U.N. Convention on the
Rights of the Child.[18] Implicit in these policies is an assumption
that children should be treated as &quot;short adults,&quot; i.e.,
as autonomous individuals, fully capable of making crucial decisions
about their upbringing, and legally entitled to make these decisions
outside the context of their family.  The second trend involves
the state's increasing propensity to substitute its judgment for
that of parents in matters relating to the upbringing and education
of children.

<p>

These trends run counter to the longstanding philosophical
and legal understanding  that with the parental responsibility
to <I>protect</I> their children from harm comes the parental
right to <I>direct</I> their children's upbringing and education.
But in cases where the state allows minors access to the full
range of choices formerly reserved for adults, parents are effectively
prevented from fulfilling their role as protector.  When the state
substitutes its judgment for that of parents by actually making
the choice for the minor, parental responsibility to guide their
children's choices is usurped.

<p>

<center><h3>'Short Adults'</h3></center>

<p>

Historically, the majority of our laws regulating minors' choices
have been of a protective nature.  For example, adults many not
enter into binding contracts with unemancipated minors, on the
assumption that a child should not be legally bound to fulfill
a contract between parties of such unequal bargaining power and
capacity.  Adults are also prohibited from selling alcohol, tobacco,
and pornography to children.  Abuse laws protect children if the
threat comes from within the family.  The law steps in to protect
the child from being harmed by a more powerful agent.

<p>

While it is indisputable that children have rights, parents
traditionally have been considered the proper custodians of these
rights until their children reach adulthood.  &quot;The presumptions
arising from the limited capacities of children account, in large
part, for their general limitation on the exercise of 'choice'
rights.  The law, and traditionally the culture, has assumed that
a basic capacity to make responsible choices is a prerequisite
to meaningful exercise of such rights.&quot;[19]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The so-called 'children's<br>
rights' movement threatens<br>
to destroy a child's most<br>
precious right: the right<br>
to childhood innocence.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The 1967 case of <I>In re Gault</I>[20] marked the Supreme Court's
first unequivocal ruling that children have constitutional rights.
While <I>Gault</I> involved juvenile court delinquency proceedings,
the Court's reasoning has far broader implications for the general
liberty of children.  Courts have begun to grant children &quot;choice&quot;
rights like adults in select areas, most notably, by guaranteeing
access to birth control and abortion.[21] This has served as a compelling
precedent for other state policies which prevent parents from
controlling minor's choice rights.

<p>

The movement to grant minors full access to the full range
of choices available to adults naturally leads to liberation of
children from their parents, who serve as an obstacle to the free
exercise of these new rights.  But in a tragic irony, the so-called
&quot;children's rights&quot; movement threatens to destroy a
child's most precious right:  the right to childhood innocence.
A startling example of this phenomenon can be found in local
public libraries.  The American Library Association is formally
opposed to any restrictions on a child's ability to check out
any item, no matter how pornographic or inappropriate for children,
regardless of parental objections.[22] The ALA has gone so far as
to refuse to let parents view the check-out records of their minor
children on grounds that such action would violate the child's
privacy rights.[23] The emotional and moral health of children is
thus sacrificed on the altar of &quot;intellectual freedom,&quot;
and parents are again prevented from fulfilling their responsibility
to protect the child.

<p>

The &quot;children's rights&quot; agenda perhaps is best embodied
in the U.N. Convention on the Rights of the Child,[24] an international
treaty adopted by the U.N. General Assembly in 1989.  According
to the United Nation's Children's Fund (UNICEF), the Convention
&quot;defines the minimum standards for civil, economic, social,
cultural, and political rights of children.&quot;[25] Ratifying nations
are called to guarantee a host of rights to children, including
&quot;the right to freedom of expression; . . . regardless of
frontiers,&quot; and the right &quot;to freedom of thought, conscience
and religion.&quot;[26]

<p>

More than 170 countries have ratified the Convention.  In February
1995, President Bill Clinton sent the treaty to the U.S. Senate
for possible ratification, where it is currently pending.  The
U.S. Constitution declares that international treaties ratified
by the U.S. become the &quot;supreme Law of the Land.&quot;[27] Therefore,
the U.N. Convention raises serious questions as to its implications
for parental rights in the U.S.  Are these &quot;children's rights&quot;
intended to be legally enforceable over and against the rights
and responsibilities of parents? What might be the scope of a
child's right, for example, to &quot;freedom of expression?&quot;[28]

<p>

<center><h3>Substituted Judgment</h3></center>

<p>

Competing interests of the family and state most frequently
meet in the public school arena.  Schools traditionally have functioned
<I>in loco parentis, i.e.,</I> in place of parents. This
implies that parents have delegated partial authority to the school.
But when school officials contradict the will or values of parents,
they exceed their delegated authority and substitute their judgment
for that of the parents.  Several recent examples from around
the country highlight the increasingly brazen tendency toward
substituted judgment in the public schools.

<p>

On March 19, 1996, 59 sixth-grade girls from the J.T. Lambert
Intermediate School in East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania, were taken
to the school nurse's office where they were required to remove
their clothes and submit to a genital examination as part of a
&quot;routine&quot; physical.  While Pennsylvania state law allows
for physical examinations at elementary schools, the East Stroudsburg
parents quite naturally did not expect such an examination to
include intrusive vaginal exams.

<p>

One family was horrified to learn that their daughter had been
forced to undergo the exam despite the fact that they had already
taken the option of submitting an exam report from their own doctor.
Their daughter reported that she had told the school official
in charge that her report was on file, but the official said
that the school had lost the report and that the girl had no choice
but to have the exam.  The girl began to cry and plead with the
school officials to use the phone to call her mother.  But she
was prohibited from calling her mother, and the school nurse stood
in front of the door, blocking the exit.  After submitting to
the exam, she came home in tears, physically and emotionally hurt.[29]

<p>

When questioned, the school initially denied that the girls
had been touched at all.  The school then abruptly changed its
position and admitted that gynecological exams had been conducted
on these 11-year-olds to check for sexually-transmitted diseases
and sexual abuse, even though no incident of disease or abuse
had been indicated.  At the time of this writing, several families
had filed suit against the school, which continues to defend its
action.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
When school officials<br>
contradict the will or<br>
values of parents, they<br>
exceed their designated<br>
authority and substitute<br>
their judgment for that<br>
of the parents.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Unfortunately, the outrage of East Stroudsburg is not an isolated
case.  In Stephens County, Georgia, Sharon and Waymon Earls were
shocked to discover that their 14- and 15-year-old daughters had
been driven to a birth control clinic by a public school staffer
without their knowledge.  The county clinic dispensed birth control
pills and condoms to the girls and administered Pap smears and
AIDS tests.  Mr. and Mrs. Earls were then denied access to the
test results by the school, which defended its actions on the
grounds that the counselor believed she was doing what was best
for the girls.  The counselor's husband, Stephens County School
Superintendent Ed Mills, admitted that his wife had driven many
other girls to the clinic over the years.[30]

<p>

Public schools are also increasingly adopting policies whereby
an entire class is subjected to mandatory psychological testing
or explicit sex education which contradicts the values taught
at home.  Psychological testing of children is often performed
under the guise of standardized tests which include intrusive
questions about the child's emotional state and sexual experiences,
the child's relationship with his or her parents, and values and
habits within the home.

<p>

For example, a 149-question survey used in Minnesota public
schools without parental approval contains questions such as:

<p><ul>

<li><i>Have you ever tried to kill yourself?

<br>

<li>How often have you run away from home?

<br>

<li>Have you felt so discouraged or hopeless that you wondered
if anything was worthwhile?</i>[31]

</ul><p>

In California, in 1994, a statewide controversy erupted over
one such test known as the California Learning Assessment System
(CLAS), a mandatory, standardized test administered to over a
million public school students.  After rumors began circulating
among parents regarding the intrusive nature of some of the questions,
the public school bureaucracy added insult to injury by refusing
to let parents even see the CLAS test their children would be
required to take.[32]

<p>

Parents who have challenged intrusive government policies in
court have met with decidedly mixed results.  Three high-profile
cases recently rejected by the U.S. Supreme Court serve as a disheartening
barometer of the status of parental rights.

<p>

<i><b>Newkirk v. Lansing:</b></i>[33]

<p>

During the 1989-1990 school
year, Daniel and Nancy Newkirk from East Lansing, Michigan, discovered
that their 8-year-old son Jason was being psychologically counseled
by an unlicensed, untrained guidance counselor against their express
wishes.  The case began when Jason's teacher told the Newkirks
that their son wasn't &quot;interacting&quot; with classmates
as she thought he should.  The parents agreed to let their son
&quot;play games&quot; (like checkers) with the guidance counselor,
but flatly refused to allow any psychological counseling.

<p>

Despite this apparent understanding, the counselor began subjecting
Jason to &quot;The Talking, Feeling, and Doing Game, a Psychotherapeutic
Game for Children.&quot;  While the manufacturer of this game
warns that it is intended for use &quot;only by mental health
professionals,&quot; the counselor had no such training.

<p>

Questions posed to young Jason from the game included:

<p><ul>

<li><i>Tell something about your mother that gets you angry.

<br>

<li>What do you think about a boy who sometimes wished that
his brother were dead?

<br>

<li>What is the worst thing you can say about your family?</i>[34]

</ul><p>

After the counseling began, the Newkirks noticed changes in
their son's attitude, and he began complaining to his parents
about his sessions with the counselor.  The Newkirks' confronted
the school, but were told that the relationship between the boy
and the counselor was &quot;confidential.&quot;  They then had
a psychiatrist examine Jason, who diagnosed the boy as having
suffered emotional damage from the sessions, including separation
anxiety disorder and panic attacks.

<p>

The Newkirks filed suit in July 1991 in U.S. District Court
against the school district and some of the school staff involved.
In March 1993, the U.S. District Court ruled against the parents.
On appeal, the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed this ruling,
and the U.S. Supreme Court refused to review the case,
leaving the Newkirks with no further remedy.

<p>

<i><b>Brown v. Hot, Sexy and Safer Productions:</b></i>[35]

<p>

In 1992, students in a Chelmsford, Massachusetts public high
school were compelled to attend a sex education seminar by Suzi
Landolph entitled &quot;Hot, Sexy, and Safer.&quot;  A transcript
of Ms. Landolph's performance in Chelmsford reveals that it included
simulated masturbation, crude language, and condom licking.  Chelmsford
parents were given neither advance notice nor a chance to remove
their children from the seminar.

<p>

Ronald and Suzanne Brown and other Chelmsford parents filed
suit, alleging that the school's &quot;opt-out&quot; policy was
not followed.  The parents lost their case before the First Circuit
Court of Appeals in Massachusetts, and in March 1996 the U.S.
Supreme Court declined to review another major parental rights
case, allowing the lower court decision against the parents to
stand.

<p>

<i><b>Curtis v. School Comm. of Falmouth:</b></i>[36]

<p>

Elizabeth Curtis and other parents from Falmouth, Massachusetts, filed 
suit in 1992 against their school board's installation of condom vending
machines in their high schools.  Moreover, according to school
board policy, school nurses were to give condoms upon request
to children as young as 11 in the junior high schools, notwithstanding
the written objections of their parents.  The County Superior
Court refused to grant a parental &quot;opt-out&quot; of the condom
program, and an appeal was rejected by the Massachusetts Supreme
Court in July 1995.  In January 1996, Bay State parents suffered
another loss when the U.S. Supreme Court refused without comment
to hear their appeal, further undermining parental rights in the
state of Massachusetts.[37]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Federal parental rights<br>
legislation would not<br>
give Congress substantive<br>
authority over areas which<br>
are properly a matter of<br>
state jurisdiction, such<br>
as education.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The Massachusetts Supreme Court maintained that because the
condom program was not &quot;coercive,&quot; the school was not
usurping parental rights:

<p><blockquote>

<i>[T]he students are free to decline to participate in the
program. . . . For their part, the plaintiffs are free to instruct
their children not to participate. . . . Although exposure to
condom vending machines and to the program itself may offend the
moral and religious sensibilities of the plaintiffs, mere exposure
to programs offered at school does not amount to unconstitutional
interference with parental liberties without the existence of
some compulsory aspects to the program.</i>[38]

</blockquote><p>

This passage from <I>Curtis</I> reveals how treating minors
as &quot;short adults&quot; works in tandem with state-substituted
judgment to undermine parental authority.  First, we are told
that the condom program is &quot;voluntary&quot; because the <I>students</I>
&quot;are free to decline to participate,&quot; <I>i.e.</I>, they
are autonomous actors capable of making their own decisions about
choices presented to them at school.  The school maintains a facade
of neutrality with regard to the choice presented, but by presenting
to the child extra-curricular options that starkly contradict
the values of the parent, the state is assisting the child in
circumventing the parent's will.

<p>

<center><h3>Reaffirming Parental Rights</h3></center>

<p>

Until recently, the primary battleground in the struggle to
preserve parental rights has been the state and federal court
system.  While individual families continue to press their case
in courts around the country, it has become increasingly clear
that parents need legislative remedies.  As a result, the parental
rights movement has become proactive, inspiring the introduction
of legislation designed to guarantee parental rights at the state
and federal levels.

<p>

In its most common form, the Parental Rights Amendment reads:
<I>&quot;The right of parents to direct the upbringing and education
of their children shall not be infringed.&quot;</I> By codifying
language taken directly from the 1925 <I>Pierce</I> case, the
Amendment would provide parents with an explicit right grounded
in their state constitution.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The federal parental<br>
rights legislation is<br>
a negative mandate on<br>
government. It checks<br>
power, not enhances it.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

A statute designed to protect parental rights has also been
introduced in Congress.  In the fall of 1995, Sen. Charles Grassley
(R-Iowa) and Rep. Steve Largent (R-Okla.) introduced the &quot;Parental
Rights and Responsibilities Act&quot; (PRRA).  The PRRA would
protect parental rights, including directing or providing for
the education of the child; making a health or mental health care
decision for the child; disciplining the child, including reasonable
corporal discipline; and directing or providing for the religious
teaching of the child. The PRRA would clarify the fundamental
nature of parental rights, thus providing much-needed direction
to federal and lower courts.

<p>

The high court in <I>Meyer</I> and <I>Pierce</I> established
that parental rights are fundamental under the liberty interest
of the Fifth and 14th Amendments to the Constitution.  The state
may not infringe a fundamental right without having a compelling
reason to do so.

<p>

In several important cases, however, lower courts have begun
to consider parental rights as less than fundamental, allowing
the state to demonstrate merely a &quot;rational basis&quot; for
infringing the right -- a much lower hurdle to clear.[39] By declining
to review lower court decisions in cases such as <I>Newkirk v.
Lansing, Brown v. Hot, Sexy, and Safer,</I> and <I>Curtis v. Falmouth</I>
-- each of which treated parental rights as less than fundamental
-- the Supreme Court has allowed the rights it enunciated long
ago in <I>Meyer</I> and <I>Pierce</I> to die the proverbial &quot;death
of a thousand cuts.&quot; 

<p>

The PRRA would codify the Supreme Court's longstanding interpretation
of parental rights as a fundamental liberty interest, and would
instruct federal and lower courts to employ the &quot;compelling
interest&quot; test when considering parental rights cases.

<p>

Some have claimed that the Parental Rights and Responsibilities
Act raises federalism concerns.  But by virtue of the rulings
in <I>Meyer, Pierce, Yoder</I> and others, the federal government,
through the Supreme Court, has already acted to protect parental
rights under the due process clause of the 14th Amendment. Congress
is given express authority to enact legislation to protect due
process rights of citizens by Section Five of the 14th Amendment.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The clash over parental rights<br>
proposals begs the fundamental<br>
question: Are ordinary parents<br>
generally competent to raise<br>
their children or should parents<br>
defer to elite authorities backed<br>
by state power?
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

It is important to remember that federal parental rights legislation
would not give Congress substantive authority over areas which
are properly a matter of state jurisdiction, such as education.
But when state regulation of education results in the violation
of  parents' constitutional rights, the federal government may
intervene to protect these rights.[40]

<p>

The federal parental rights legislation would not expand government
by creating a new federal &quot;program.&quot;  The PRRA would
not increase federal spending or require a new federal administrative
agency. Rather, the PRRA is a <I>negative</I> mandate on government.
It checks power, not enhances it.

<p>

<center><h3>The Fundamental Question: Who Decides?</h3></center>

<p>

Critics of both the federal parental rights bill and the state
constitutional amendments typically claim that parental rights
laws would make it tougher for the state to protect children from
abuse, and would give one parent the right to dictate school curriculum
for everyone else's child, leading to education gridlock.

<p>

These and most other criticisms are grounded in the mistaken
notion that these proposals would provide an <I>absolute</I> right
for parents, which would override any state interest in the welfare
and education of children.  But as both proposals seek to codify
the Meyer-Pierce doctrine, the well-established limits to parental
rights under this doctrine would continue to apply.

<p>

For example, in <I>Prince</I>, the high court made it clear
that &quot;neither the right of religion <I>nor the rights of
parents are beyond limitation</I>&quot; (Emphasis added).
<I>Prince</I> identified numerous areas in which the state may set
limits on parental rights, such as compulsory school attendance,
mandatory vaccination policies, and child labor laws.  And in
<I>Runyon v. McCrary,</I>[41] the Supreme Court held that parents
&quot;have no constitutional right to provide their children with
. . . education unfettered by reasonable government regulation.&quot;
All constitutional rights have their limits, and parental rights
are no exception.

<p>

The clash over parental rights proposals begs the fundamental
question: <I>Who decides what's in the best interests of childen?
Parents? Or the government?</I>  Are ordinary parents generally
competent to raise their children or should parents defer to elite
authorities backed by state power?

<p>

Unable to attack the underlying constitutional doctrine of
parent's rights, yet adamantly opposed to the people acting to
codify this doctrine through the democratic process, opponents
sometimes find themselves in the awkward position best expressed
by Elliot Mincberg, Executive Director of People for the American
Way, in criticizing the state Parental Rights Amendment: &quot;Our
view is that the Amendment is either unnecessary or it would seriously
conflict with the current legal notion of parental rights and
responsibilities.&quot;[42] Presumably, parental rights laws are
&quot;unnecessary&quot; in light of Supreme Court cases, which,
if codified, would be somehow radical and dangerous.

<p>

Other opponents go a step further in making explicit the fact
that parental rights laws are incompatible with the &quot;children's
rights&quot; agenda.  Professor Barbara Bennett Woodhouse of 
the University of Pennsylvania has written that the child should
be seen as &quot;having a direct relationship with government
. . . as public resource and public ward, entitled both to make
claims upon the community and to be claimed by the community.&quot;[43]
Prof. Woodhouse believes that focusing on parents' individual
rights &quot;objectifies&quot; children, and that the law should
concentrate on whether parents have &quot;earned&quot; the authority
they exercise over the child.[44]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Recognizing the irreplacable<br>
role of parents is essential<br>
to keeping the power of the<br>
state in check, revitalizing<br>
citizenship, and ensuring<br>
that children receive the<br>
love, protection and guidance<br>
only a parent can provide.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

How might parents &quot;earn&quot; their authority? Perhaps
through government-mandated licensing of parents, as proposed
by Dr. Jack C. Westman, professor of psychiatry at the University
of Wisconsin. &quot;Just as individual responsibility for driving
a car is certified by a driver's license, the individual responsibility
of a parent for child rearing would be certified by a parenting
license.&quot;[45] Requiring parents to obtain a government license
before being allowed to conceive and bear children would complete
the shift from the state acting <I>in loco parentis</I> to the
state <I>as</I> parent. Primary authority over children would
inhere in the state, which would then delegate its authority to
the biological parents of the child -- assuming they pass the
exam.[46]

<p>

<center><h3>Linking Rights and Responsibilities</h3></center>

<p>

If successful, the parental rights movement will provide parents
with greater legal standing to ensure that government respects
their rights through its policies, and, when necessary, in the
courts.  But beyond this immediate, practical benefit, a national
debate on parental rights also has great potential to foster more
parental responsibility.

<p>

The key to encouraging greater parental responsibility is to
explicitly recognize the link between rights and duties upon which
this nation was founded, and to renew our optimism in the ability
of the people to manage their own affairs, as citizens and as
parents.  Indeed, &quot;the most terribly important things must
be left to ordinary men themselves,&quot; including the right
of parents to protect their children from harmful influences and
to direct their children's upbringing.  Recognizing the irreplaceable
role of parents is essential to keeping the power of the state
in check, revitalizing citizenship, and ensuring that children
receive the love, protection and guidance only a parent can provide.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>-- by FRC Director of Legal Studies Cathleen A. Cleaver, Esq.
and Greg Erken, Executive Director for Of the People.  FRC Intern
Keith Bannach also contributed to this report.</i>

