<center><h1>Staff</h1></center>
<p>
<dt><b><a name="Anir"> Paul Anir </a></b>
<ul>Paul Anir serves the Foundation as a Research Associate.  Anir was employed
by Idaho State University as an administrator in various positions. The most
recent was as Coordinator for Development & Special Projects and Special
Advisor for Institutional Advancement.
</ul><p>
<dt><b><a name="Dusek">Libor Dusek</a></b>
<ul>Libor Dusek is a citizen of the Czech Republic.  Mr. Dusek joined the Progress &amp: Freedom Foundation as a Researcher in 1995.  He is involved in the <a href="/pff/i-energy.html" target="_top">Energy Project</a> and his primary responsibility is data collection and analysis.  He received his degree in Economics at Charles University in Prague and worked at Wold Bank as an assistant for economic experiments in Central Europe.
</ul>
<P>
<dt><b><a name="Epler">Katherine Epler</a></b>

<ul>As director of special events and assistant director of
development, Epler manages the Foundation's Brown Bag luncheon series,
conferences, Congressional seminars and project summits. She also coordinates
activities for the Committee For American Progress and other contributor outreach
efforts. Prior to joining the Foundation, Epler served as a task force director
on health care issues at the American Legislative Exchange Council. She has also
worked at the <a href="http://www.cato.org/main/">Cato Institute</a> and in the Office of Representative John R. Kasich.</ul>
<P>
<dt><b><a name="Krajc">Rachel Krajc</b></a>
<ul>
 As project assistant to the Foundation's senior fellows, Krajc focuses her efforts toward the <a href="/pff/i-mip.html" target="_top">Medical Innovation</a> and <a href="/pff/i-energy.html" target="_top">Energy Transmission</a> projects.  She devotes the majority of her time to actively working with Senior Fellow Jane Fortson on the Foundation's housing project.  Additionally, Krajc coordinates Senior Fellow Mike Vlahos' activities as he vigorously pursues the ongoing transformation of American life; <a href="/pff/i-bigc.html" target="_top">the Big Change</a>.
</ul><P>
<dt><b><a name=Lassman>Kent Lassman</a></b><ul>
Kent Lassman joined the Foundation in May 1994.  He worked as a Research
Associate for the <a href="/pff/political_renewal.html">Center for Political Renewal</a> to help produce the forthcoming monograph of Foundation senior fellow, <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Weber">Vin Weber</a>.  Currently his work is focused upon helping to discover the role and composition of government in the future of America’s housing policies.  He is working closely with senior fellow Jane Fortson who leads PFF’s project, "The Future of HUD and the Nation’s Housing Policy."  Additionally, Mr. Lassman provides occasional research support for the books, essays, congressional testimony and op-eds of Foundation President Jeffrey Eisenach. 
</ul><p>

<dt><b><a name=Lee>Julianne Lee</a></b><ul>
Julianne Lee serves as Project Director for The Progress & Freedom
Foundation's
 <a href="/pff/cyberspace.html">
Cyberspace and Telecommunications Studies Program</a>. She directs
the project's research and outreach efforts, manages its Telecom
Working Group of leading scholars, and represents the Foundation
at Congressional and other Federal telecommunications activities.
<p>
Ms. Lee works on issues including reform of the electromagnetic
spectrum, tlecommunications industry deregulation, encryption and
copyright policy, and the nature and development of Cyberspace.
<p>
Currently, Ms. Lee serves as an Advisory Board member to the U.S.
Congressional
Internet Caucus chaired by Congressman Rick White (R-WA) and she
sits on the Advisory Board of the Internet Guild. Ms. Lee managed
the Foundation's annual cyberspace conference, Aspen Summir '95.
She also served as producer and director of an eight-week
Congressional Seminar, <i> The Meaning of the Information
Revolution</i>, designed to educate Members of Congress and their
staff on the social, economic and political implications of the
Information Age.
<p>
Ms. Lee has discussed telecommunications deregulation issues on
<i>The Progress Report</i>, a national cable-television talk show,
 co-hosted by House Speaker Newt Gingrich. Formerly, she worked at
Morrison & Foerster with Cheryl A. Tritt, former chief of the
Common Carrier Bureau at the FCC.
</ul>
<P>

<dt><b><a name="McCoy">Garland McCoy</a></b>

<ul>Garland McCoy is the Vice President for Development for the Foundation.
Prior to joining PFF, he was the Vice President of Development for The American
Legislative Exchange Council from 1989 to 1994. McCoy served in several key
positions during the Reagan administration. These included an administrative
position at the <a href="http://www.whithouse.gov">White House</a> and staff assistant to the Secretary of the Army. He
also was senior consultant to Secretary of Education William Bennett.</ul>
<p>
<dt><b><a name ="Murphy">Jill Murphy</a></b>
<ul>Jill Murphy, a native of Princeton, New Jersey joined PFF in January 1996.
 As a Project Assistant to Director of Regulatory Studies, Tom Lenard, she
works on the Medical Innovation, Environment, and Energy projects.  Formerly
Ms. Murphy was employed by Princeton University as the Human Resources
Information Systems Administrator (Database Administrator for short) and
prior to that she spent 7 years in the retail banking industry.

</ul><p>
<dt><b><a name="O_Donnell">Richard F. O'Donnell</a></b><ul>
Richard F. O'Donnell is Director of Communications at The Progress & Freedom
Foundation. He serves as editor of all Foundation policy
reports, books and articles. In addition, he is responsible
for media  relations and public outreach.
 His editorials have appeared in <i>Investor's Business Daily</i>,
<i>The Washington Times</i> and <i>Commonsense</i>.
<p>
Mr. O'Donnell is currently assisting
former Congressman Vin Weber on his book
 about the new political majority emerging in American politics. He has also
 worked with columnist Arianna Huffington, author Marvin Olasky, and
numerous policy and Congressional leaders in the telecommunications,
health care, energy, environment and welfare reform fields.
<p>
Mr. O'Donnell is a recognized authority on
the nature and political ramifications
of the transition from the Industrial Age to the Digital Age.
Writing and speaking
on the survivability of the American Idea in the 21<sup>st</sup> Century,
 he is a columnist for the cyberspace magazine <i>Upside Online</i>.
<p>
He was managing producer of a weekly television show,
<i>The Progress Report</i>
, co-hosted by Heather Higgins and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and editor
of the <i>American Civilization</i>. Mr. O'Donnell has also worked at the
National Policy Forum: A republican Center of the Exchange of Ideas and
at the Archer Daniels Midland Company.
<p>
A native of Colorado, Mr. O'Donnell is a graduate of the Colorado College,
and has studied at Boston College and The London School of Economics
and Political Science.
</ul><p>
<dt><b><a name="Rock">Emily Rock</a></b>
<ul>Rock is vice president of operations at the Foundation.  Prior to joining PFF she was executive assistant to James C. Miller III, Foundation board member and counselor for Citizens for a Sound Economy.  Rock has also served as associate director of Community Partnership, a substance abuse prevention program in New Mexico, and was secretary to the Federal Trade Commission from 1983-1988.
</ul><P>
<dt><b><a name="Sparks">Michael G. Sparks</a></b>
<ul>As manager of public relations for the Foundation, Sparks is responsible for extending the vision and message of the organization to its members and the public as a whole. As such, he is responsible for the Foundation's Internet presence and monograph series.  Prior to this, Sparks was legislative director for energy, environment and natural resource issues at the American Legislative Exchange Council.
</ul><P>
<dt><b><a name="Teske">Richard Teske</a></b>
<ul>Richard Teske is Vice President for External Affairs for the Foundation. Prior to joining the Foundation, he was a corporate officer and Vice President for Federal Government Relations and Public Policy for Burroughs Wellcome, an international pharmaceutical company.  He held numerous positions in the Reagan Administrations, including Delegate to the United Nations Conference on Social and Economic Policy, Liaison to the White House for the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS), Deputy Assistant Secretary for HHS and Associate Administrator for the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA).
</ul>
<P>
<dt><b><a name = "Winters">Hilary Winters </a></b>
<ul>Hilary Winters is assistant director for Senior Fellow Michael Vlahos’ joint project with the Japanese think-tank, Asian Forum Japan.  This project investigates the ongoing transformation of American life - the Big Change - and how that transformation will affect change in Japan.  Prior to joining PFF, Winters worked as a country risk analyst/mining economist for The Winters Company – a Tucson, Arizona based mining consulting firm.  She researched countries and compiled multifaceted reports assessing	risks for potential investors, with a concentration in Central and Latin American
countries.
</ul><p>

<dt><b><a name="Wright">Elizabeth Wright</a></b>

<ul>As project director for the <a href="/pff/i-mip.html">Medical Innovation Project</a>,
Wright formulates and manages the projects research and advisory committee
activities, directs its outreach program and arranges conferences. Prior to
coming to the Foundation, she was a Legislative Director at a government
relations firm that specialized in <a href="http://www.fda.gov/">Food 
and Drug Administration</a>, health and
medical research issues. She also served as the Special Assistant in Public
Affairs at the FDA during the Bush presidency.</ul>
<p>

<p>


