<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Executive Summary -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>

<P>
<h2>ADVANCING MEDICAL INNOVATION:</h2>
<P>
<B>Health, Safety and the Role of Government in the 21st Century</B>
<P>
<B>Executive Summary</B>
<P>
by 
Ralph A. Epstein, M.D., Thomas M. Lenard, Ph.D, Henry I. Miller, M.D., Robert D. Tollison, Ph.D., W. Kip Viscusi, Ph.D., William M. Wardell, M.D., Ph.D.
<P>
As Americans enter the 21st Century, we are poised to see tremendous
breakthroughs in medical technology - from genetic engineering
to surgical lasers to molecular transports.  Yet patients may
be denied these advances because the process for allowing new
medical products on the market is cumbersome, slow, expensive
and inefficient.  In order for Americans to have the latest technology
to improve their health - or even to survive - the Food and Drug
Administration - a prototypical centralized, bureaucratic regulatory
agency - must be reformed for the 21st Century.
<P>
While reforms have been tried in the past, they failed to significantly
improve the speed with which patients have access to new  products;
failed reforms have been too marginal to make an impact.  Therefore,
the following plan calls for a completely new framework for approving
drugs and medical devices.  Its goal is simple:  the regulatory
process should be designed to block dangerous or ineffective products
while also speeding safe and effective ones to the clinic.  While
such a system will have a great impact on stopping the flight
of our medical companies overseas and maintaining American global
competitiveness, its fundamental benefit will be to save lives
and increase the quality of life for Americans.
<P>
Currently the FDA has a statutory monopoly on new product approvals.
 This monopoly eliminates any institutional check on the regulatory
creep that inexorably has added time, costs and unpredictability
to the review process.  These effects have stifled the development
and introduction of new technologies to patients.  As long as
the only route to market is through the FDA, adverse trends in
product availability will continue.
<P>
Therefore, our plan opens the product certification process to
competitive forces.  It is not a complete laissez faire approach
with no government oversight, because Americans want a required
independent review to ensure safety and effectiveness.  While
maintaining the existing legal requirements for pre-market demonstration
of safety and effectiveness, as well as the FDA stamp of apporval,
the plan relies on nongovernmental bodies - called Drug or Device
Certification Bodies - to review and certify new products.
<P>
The competition among the DCBs for clients will encourage them
to offer the greatest expertise and reputation for integrity,
to identify and solve problems early and rapidly, to perform reviews
in a timely manner, and to manage the oversight and review efficiently.
 The FDA's primary function will be to certify the quality of
the certifiers, not to actually be a certifier of products.  The
FDA retains authority to issue the final sign-off approval for
product marketing, but with a new appeal procedure in the event
of disagreement with a company and/or DCB.  Also, the FDA retains
a powerful post-marketing  system for monitoring the safety of
products.
<P>
Specific highlights of the plan are as follows:
<P>
<B>DRUGS AND BIOLOGICS</B>
<P>
 
<UL>
<LI>For drugs and biologics, the primary responsibility for managing
the Investigational New Drug filing, oversight of the clinical
program, and New Drug Application/Product License Application
review will be transferred from the FDA to nongovernmental Drug
Certification Bodies (DCBs).  The DCBs, which can be profit-making
or non-profit organizations, will be subject to FDA certification
and staffed - as required by the language of the Food, Drug, and
Cosmetic Act - by the necessary &quot;experts qualified by scientific
training and experience.&quot;  
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The sponsor will submit New Drug Applications/Product License
Applications to the DCB, not to FDA.  After evaluating the application,
the DCB will submit a summary of the results of its review (if
favorable) to FDA.  The FDA Commissioner then has a designated
period of time to accept the DCB's recommendation for approval
(which, legally, is a &quot;rebuttable presumption&quot;) or to
deny approval.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B>MEDICAL DEVICES</B>
<UL>
<LI>Manufacturers generally will have a choice of methods by which
to get a product approved for market, by either demonstrating
conformance of its<I> quality assurance systems</I> or conformance
of the <I>product</I> itself.  Such a system is modeled on the
European Union's medical device regulatory system, which is characterized
by reliance on clear and objective standards that are largely
implemented by private, nongovernmental organizations.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>For all classes of devices except Class I (the least risky),
a DCB must audit the manufacturer periodically to confirm conformance
with the necessary standards.  The FDA's current auditing of manufacturers
for Good Manufacturing Practices will be replaced by the DCB's
certification of the manufacturer's quality assurance systems.
 Such certification will often exceed FDA standards as it could
include certification of design quality assurance.  It will also
be performed far more frequently than current FDA inspections.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Class III products (the riskiest products) will require premarketing
<I>design approval</I> by a DCB.  Although not part of the EU
system, the plan also requires the FDA to be notified 90 days
prior to marketing a Class III product, to allow time for the
FDA to elect to review the appropriateness of the certification
process.
</UL>

<P>
<B>APPEALS</B>
<P>
<ul>
Our plan establishes an independent, standing committee of experts
within the Department of Health and Human Services - the Medical
Review Board (MRB) - to advise the Secretary when the FDA disagrees
with a DCB's product approval recommendation.  The MRB will have
approximately 10 to 15 members representing a wide spectrum of
scientific, medical and regulatory expertise.  It will hear appeals
of FDA decisions to overturn a DCB recommendation, and will advise
the HHS Secretary.  All parties, including FDA, will be expected
to accept the decision of the Secretary.
</ul><P>
<B>LIABILITY</B>
<P>
<ul>
The plan includes a regulatory compliance defense for all product
liability, not simply a defense against punitive damages.<B> 
</B>The regulatory compliance defense recognizes that, by negotiating
the regulatory process, the manufacturer has fulfilled its requirements
with respect to the provision of products that provide an appropriate
level of safety, and that the government has certified this fact.
 Lawyers and courts should not be second guessing decisions regarding
product safety that have already been recognized by government
agencies as having achieved appropriate levels of safety.  Our
plan for replacing the FDA drug and device approval processes
would not limit the applicability of this defense, because there
would continue to be a regulatory mechanism to ensure that an
appropriate level of product safety is provided to consumers.
<P>
Of course DCBs will be subject to tort liability for negligence
in carrying out their obligations. Our plan recommends formalizing
the current recognition by the courts that such certification
bodies not be subject to strict liability to third parties injured
by products.
</ul>
<P>
<B>INTERNATIONAL HARMONIZATION</B>
<P>
<ul>
Our plan recommends that products approved in jurisdictions whose
standards are similar to those in the United States - for example,
Great Britain or the European Union - have the same status as
a product certified by a DCB.  Where applicable (i.e., for drugs
and Class III devices), products with foreign approvals could
be submitted to the FDA for U.S. marketing approval under the
same procedures and with the same rebuttable presumptions as a
DCB-approved product.
</ul><P>

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
